Heart Rate Variability (HRV) Analysis: A Methodology for Organizational Neuroscience

4

5

In recent years, organizational and management research has looked with increasing attention

6

7

at the use of neuroscience in its domains, with a growing number of contributions converging in the

8

9

emerging field of organizational neuroscience (ON; Becker, Cropanzano, & Sanfey, 2011; Senior,

10

11

Lee, & Butler, 2011)1. Notwithstanding this interest, both the theoretical works and the few empirical

12

13

studies seen thus far in ON have predominantly focused on the brain and on brain-imaging

14

15

techniques, such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and electroencephalography

16

17

(EEG) (e.g., Bagozzi et al., 2013; Waldman, Balthazard, & Peterson, 2011). Conversely, there has

18

For Peer Review

19

been an overall lack of research exploring insights derived from analysis of the fuller activities of the

20

21

human nervous system and embracing the wide-ranging methodological toolkit that modern

22

23

neuroscience can insert into organizational scholarship.

24

25

Notably, measurements associated with the activity of the autonomic nervous system (ANS)2,

26

27

like cardiovascular measures, electrodermal activity (EDA or galvanic skin response), and blood

28

29 30

pressure variation, have been largely disregarded in ON thus far. This knowledge shortage is highly

31 32

surprising because these are known outcomes of the nervous system’s activities and/or responses—

33 34

thus “neuroscience measures” in their own right—and certainly relevant for quantitative observations

35

36

of psychological and social phenomena pertaining to organizational studies. For one, cognate

37

38

disciplines like social psychology and social neuroscience (e.g., Cacioppo, 1994; Cacioppo &

39

40

Sandman, 1978; Cacioppo, Tassinary, & Berntson, 2000; Cameron, 2002) have already established

41

42

the value of examining ANS responses to indicate variations in several constructs, ranging from

43

44

emotions (e.g., Quintana, Guastella, Outhred, Hickie, & Kemp, 2012) to social interactions (e.g.,

45

46

Blascovich, Mendes, Hunter, Lickel, & Kowai-Bell, 2001). Indeed, the ANS responses measured can

47

48

represent antecedents of conscious awareness (Bechara, Damasio, Tranel, & Damasio, 1997), map

49

50

differences amongst emotions (Levenson, 1992), and also inform on complex cognitive processes,

51

52

such as reasoning about social dilemmas (Grossmann, Sahdra, & Ciarrochi, 2016), which may be

53

54

difficult to fully appreciate by means of more conventional research methods.

55

56

Moreover, and this is of particular interest for the managerial literature, the associated ANS

57

58

methods allow for a constructive address of some conceptual and practical challenges currently

59

60

http://mc.manuscriptcentral.com/orm

