Because of the high variability of the RR series, it is challenging to infer reliable information

31 32

on ANS outflow from these tachograms. Yet, the use of HRV analysis in inferring neuroscience

33 34

information from these signals becomes clearer in Figure 6. Here, we show the derived histograms of

35

36

the mean of the heart rate (bpm) and related time domain measures for the same subject. At rest the

37

38

subject presents an average HR of 74±7 bmp. In Figure 6 (b) the average HR remains within a normal

39

40

range, yet slightly shifted toward higher values than in Figure 6 (a) at 81±8 bmp. Remarkably, during

41

42

the high mental effort condition the histogram is evidently shifted toward higher values (121±5 bmp).

43

44

Simply put, as we can intuitively expect, the subject’s heart rate is faster while performing the more

45

46

demanding task.

47

48

Importantly, time domain measures are strongly influenced by changes in both sympathetic

49

50

and parasympathetic activity, making them non-specific measures of autonomic modulation. In our

51

52

case, one possible approach to quantitatively appreciate such influence is to calculate the root mean

53

54

square of the successive differences between adjacent RR intervals (RMSSD). Generally speaking,

55

56

this measure provides a fairly sensitive time domain measurement of parasympathetic activity.

57

58

59

60

