1While acknowledging different views on organizational neuroscience present in the

6

7

literature, with parsimony and inclusiveness in mind, here we refer to organizational neuroscience as

8

9

that field using neuroscience theories, findings, practices, and/or methods to advance knowledge of

10

11

organizational and management science, and vice versa.

12

13

2Given the complexity of the ANS, the available assessments of its activity are multiple, and

14

15

there is not yet a single test that precisely reflects the function of a specific branch of this system.

16

17

Here, by referring to ANS methods, we generally encompass advanced methods to assess heart-rate

18

For Peer Review

19

variability, baroreflex testing, and sweat output, which are primarily used for research purposes (Hilz

20

21

& Dütsch, 2006). For the sake of completeness, other ANS methods involve the assessment of

22

23

circulating catecholamines, microneurography, scintigraphic, and tests of autonomic reflexes, among

24

25

others. These are generally used in clinical settings and are not routinely available.

26

27

3Together with the sympathetic and parasympathetic, a separate component of the ANS is

28

29 30

the enteric nervous system (ENS), the intrinsic nervous system of the gastrointestinal tract (for a

31 32

review, see Mayer, 2011). This system is relatively independent not only from the CNS but also from

33 34

the other districts of the ANS.

35 36

4Vagal regulation is mediated through release of acetylcholine; the sympathetic regulation is

37

38

mediated through epinephrine and norepinephrine. The acetylcholine promotes the response of

39

40

muscarinic receptors, which in turn decrease the speed of the myocardium depolarization and promote

41

42

decay in the heart rate. The epinephrine and norepinephrine have an opposite behavior; they activate

43

44

the β-adrenergic receptors, resulting in acceleration of the myocardium depolarization and in higher

45

46

heart rate. Note that this regulation mechanism does not have a direct effect on the nodes.

47

48

5Sometimes a U wave—of similar shape to a T wave but of lower amplitude—may follow the

49

50

T wave. The U wave is usually seen in people with low heart rates and rarely when HR is high.

51

52

6During time intervals of various lengths, research subjects are asked to count their heartbeats

53

54

silently without taking any reference (i.e., their pulse), and this measure is compared to their actual

55

56

HR over the same time period in order to determine participants’ heartbeat perception, often

57

58

59

60

http://mc.manuscriptcentral.com/orm

